{"cursor":"14166","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\"'Break a leg'\" is a well-known idiom in theatre which means \"good luck.\" It is\ntypically said to actors and musicians before they go on stage to perform. The\norigin of the phrase is obscure.\n\nThe expression reflects a theatrical superstition in which wishing a person\n\"good luck\" is considered bad luck. The\nexpression is sometimes used outside the theatre as superstitions and customs\ntravel through other professions and then into common use. Among professional\ndancers, the traditional saying is not \"break a leg,\" but \"merde\".\n","linknr":263,"url":"Break_a_leg","recorded":1362551904,"links":15,"instances":["food","play"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Theatre","Stage terminology","Superstitions","English idioms"],"headings":["Origins","Alternate terms","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f8/Wiktionary-logo-en.svg/37px-Wiktionary-logo-en.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["richard_iii","play"],["chicken","food"]],"members":["chicken","richard_iii"],"related":["Idiom","Theatre","Luck","Actor","Musician","Theatrical_superstition","Dance","Robert_Wilson_Lynd","Edna_Ferber","Edna_Ferber","Bernard_Sobel","Bernard_Sobel","Curtain_call","Ancient_Greece","Ancient_Rome","Gladiator","Colosseum","Yiddish_language","German_language","Polish_language","Abraham_Lincoln_assassination","John_Wilkes_Booth","Ford's_Theatre","Richard_III_(play)","British_people","David_Garrick","Vaudeville","Renaissance","Theater_drapes_and_stage_curtains","Proscenium","Spel","Hex","Rotwelsch","Yiddish","Theatre_of_Australia","Chicken_(food)","Macbeth","The_Scottish_play","Thespis","Knocking_on_wood","San_Diego_Reader"]}